eminiscences -- t79. The Teacher's Source of Authority -- t80. Address on Receiving the Royal Bank Award -- t81. Installation Address as Chancellor -- t82. The Chancellor's Message -- t83. Criticism as Education -- t84. The Beginning of the Word -- t85. Installation of Alvin A. Lee -- t86. The View from Here -- t87. The Authority of Learning -- t88. Language as the Home of Human Life -- t89. On Living inside Real Life -- t90. Farewell to Goldwin French -- t91. Foreword to English Studies at Toronto -- t92. Preface to On Education -- t93. Preface to From Cobourg to Toronto -- t94. Unpublished Introduction to Beyond Communication -- t95. Woman Heads University -- tAppendix. Educational Pieces Omitted from The Collected Works -- t Notes -- tEmendations -- t Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume brings together 95 different pieces on education by Northrop Frye, dating from 1931 to 1989. It traces Frye's thinking about education from his student days through the campus unrest of the 1960s and the more recent budgetary crises facing higher education in Canada. Frye's consistent affirmation that the goal of a liberal education is to make one maladjusted may give some hint as to the richness and variety of the writings collected here.Among the range of subjects that Frye addresses are teaching (from kindergarten to university), literary studies, the nature of the university, student radicalism, educational policy and procedure, and particular occasions in the life of Victoria University. The volume includes articles, speeches, reports, a short book, introductions, letters to the editor, and some obscure and newly discovered texts. As former students and colleagues of Frye, the editors have brought personal as well as scholarly knowledge to the volume. Each provides part of the introduction: the first placing the works in the context of Frye's biography and the changes in university education over his lifetime; the other discussing them theoretically and in relation to his ideas about literature and the imagination.Frye was influential not only as a theorist of education but as a teacher and administrator. His writings on education are a central part of his life's work, and no Frye scholar or enthusiast should be without them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aEducationxPhilosophy. 0aEducationzCanada. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aEstate of Northrop Frye, , eeditor.1 aFrench, Goldwin Sylvester, eeditor.1 aO'Grady, Jean, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442677913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442677913.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG